{
  "text": "two bacterial toxicity tests were used to determine acute toxicity of soil water extract -Vibrio fischeri bioluminescence inhibition test -Microtox (iSo 1998) and Pseudomonas putida growth inhibition test (iSo 10712, 1995) . Soil was extracted by deionised water (for P. putida growth inhibition test) and a solution of 2% naCl (for the Microtox test). Soil extracts were prepared in a ratio of 1:2 (soil to water or 2% naCl) but for two samples (a 30 m and B 30 m) the extraction ratio was 1:4 (soil to water or 2% naCl) because of the high sorption capacity of the samples. in all cases 5 g of soil samples were used for extraction. if the pH of the extract was not in the optimum range 6-8 it was adjusted to pH 7. the P. putida test was performed as a miniaturized microplate growth inhibition assay according to [CITATION_1] in growth medium according to iSo 10712 (1995) . the optical density of samples was measured at 436 nm after 16 h incubation at 23\u00b0C using a microplate spectrophotometer. the results were related to the response measured in the growth medium and expressed in percents. the luminescence inhibition of V. fischeri was detected by a luminometer after 15 and 30 min exposition at 15\u00b0C. the results were related to the luminescence in pure medium (2% naCl) and expressed in percentual values.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "84378964"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "84378964": {
      "title": "Miniaturized kinetic growth inhibition assays with Vibrio fischeri and Pseudomonas putida (application, validation and comparison)",
      "abstract": "Abstract Two miniaturized growth inhibition assays with Vibrio fischeri and Pseudomonas putida , based on the German DIN Standards 38 412-37 and 38 412-8 are presented. Different calculation modes are compared on the basis of measuring toxicological effects (EC 50 and EC 20 values) of several heavy metals and other reference substances. They demonstrate the higher sensitivity of the Pseudomonas putida test. The results point out the insufficiency of the endpoint calculation mode. Therefore, a modified integral data analysis procedure is recommended. Possibilities and limits of the test protocols and kinetic data recordings are discussed."
    }
  }
}